### A3. Threat-model addenda framing

**One-line shape.** Late-round pass against 3–6 attacker objectives;
route each finding to in-scope absorption, discipline note, or named
downstream forward-action.

**Rejection.** Closing design on feature completeness without a
priority-1 adversarial pass against named objectives. Per-finding review
misses findings no individual item suggests; the objective frame
clusters them (cache poisoning, FFI exploitation, resource DoS, etc.).

**Reopening criteria.** Skip the threat-model round only when the
sub-PR's pre-flight reviewer-map shows zero cryptographic,
consensus, or untrusted-input surfaces — pure orchestration with no
new attack surface. If substrate later adds such a surface, reopen via
design-round 1 of that sub-PR with a fresh objective enumeration.

**Re-evaluation shape.** New plan-doc section (2c's shape: §5.11)
with objective table, disposition per finding `(a) in-scope`, `(b)
discipline note`, `(c) forward-action`, and cross-links in §13 /
target plan-doc scaffolds.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **Per-finding whack-a-mole after "design closed."** Round 4
  posture-shift: closure means closure **plus active defense**, not
  freeze (`RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2C_PLAN.md` §14 Round 5 posture-shift
  note).
- **Threat-model findings with no route.** A finding without
  absorb-or-carry disposition is institutional knowledge loss.

**Precedents.**

- Round 4 §5.11: six objectives → T1'–T8' in-scope; §5.11.5–7
  forward-actions to 2f/2g/3a (`RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2C_PLAN.md` §5.11).
- §5.11.8 ties Objective 6 (consensus split) to audit-against-actual-
  code — threat-model and audit disciplines compose, not duplicate.

---

### A4. Reversion-clause for sub-PR boundary changes

**One-line shape.** Scope moves between sub-PRs need substrate-
anchored reasoning and named reopening criteria; boundary stability
comes from named reasoning, not inertia.

**Rejection.** Silent scope migration (work "was 2e, now 2c") without
documented substrate motivation and reopening criteria. Applies
`21-reversion-clause-discipline.mdc` at sub-PR altitude — do not
restate that rule here; cite it for the three-part shape.

**Reopening criteria.** A deferred boundary (e.g., "trait stays for
later sub-PR") reopens when a **named production caller** or
**consensus event** requires the abstracted surface now — not when a
contributor prefers convenience. F4 example: trait-based cache mock
reopens if 2f/3a integration tests need a mock with multiple impls and
design-round 1 documents the caller (`§5.4` forward-action).

**Re-evaluation shape.** Plan-doc section naming old boundary, new
boundary, substrate evidence, parent-plan revision artifact if
phases renumbered, and FOLLOWUPS/CHANGELOG if user-visible scope
shift.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **"The boundary is the boundary."** Refusal-forever without criteria;
  brittle when substrate shifts.
- **Absorb without parent-plan alignment.** F4 required
  `RANDOMX_V2_PLAN.md` phase deletion — scope move plus track
  enumeration update.

**Precedents.**

- F4: `Cache::derive` absorbed from planned 2e into 2c; eliminates
  `DatasetReader` trait + mock (`§5.4`; PR #66).
- R2-D1: trait → free function within Round 1 locked dispositions —
  structural tightening, not scope creep (`§14` Round 2).

---

### A5. Forward-action propagation convention

**One-line shape.** Every finding routes to **absorb now** or **carry
to named PR scaffold** with the decision recorded in both source and
target docs.

**Rejection.** Findings that live only in a closed plan-doc's prose —
downstream authors re-derive or miss carries. Institutional knowledge
at one-PR-per-contributor risk.

**Reopening criteria.** Inline absorption instead of forward-action
when the downstream sub-PR is **not yet scaffolded** and the work is
≤~100 LoC with zero consensus coupling to the downstream phase —
record the exception in the source plan-doc with why inline was cheaper
than carry. Otherwise carry.

**Re-evaluation shape.** Source: §13 forward-path bullet or §5.11.x
forward-action subsection. Target: downstream plan-doc §1 or §3
"inherited forward-actions" with ID (e.g., R4 §5.11.6 → 3a FFI
hardening). Close the carry when the target PR lands the work.

**Anti-patterns.**

- **"2d will figure it out."** Without scaffold carry, 2d Round 1
  re-derives FPU, F128, CFROUND pointers from scratch.
- **Carry without target anchor.** Forward-action must name phase +
  plan-doc section, not "later."

**Precedents.**

- §13: 2d/2f/2g/3a inheritance lists with R4 §5.11.x IDs
  (`RANDOMX_V2_PHASE2C_PLAN.md` §13).
- §5.11.6 → 3a: null-check, length validation, `*const [u8; 32]`,
  `ERR_NULL_PTR` taxonomy — each item copied to 3a scaffold when
  drafted.

